obj_root_law_sections_1_content:
  string
  line 1
  line `THE MADRAS CITY LAND REVENUE ACT, 1851`
  line `A CT N O. 12 OF 1851`
  line `[ Passed on the 14 th November, 1851.]`
  line `1. Assessable lands in Madras not assessed, to be assessed at customary rates.`
  line `2. Lakhiraj tenures of sixty years standing and none of less to be valid.`
  line `3. Collector to determine rate of assessment, subject to an appeal.`
  line `4, 5, 6. Collector may have rent - paying lands measured to ascertain the exactness of assessed`
  line `quantity: and (5) order an abatement when assessed at too much; and (6) an incr ease when assessed at`
  line `too little.`
  line `7. After demand in writing, rent may be recovered by distress and sale of goods and chattels. Colle ctor`
  line `may appoint bailiffs and appraisers to make and appraise, &c. d istresses.`
  line `8. Rent paid to East India Company by under tenant may be deducted by him from his own rent.`
  line `9. Land revenue or rent of East India Company to have priority over all other claims as respects`
  line `property liable.`
  line `10. Distress to proceed notwithstanding liability d isputed, unless amount is deposited.`
  line `11. A rrears of rent removeable for six years after due or after acknowledgement in writing.`
  line `12. Claim to hold land rent free to be referred by Collector to Board, if disa llowed by B oard, land to`
  line `be assessed, subject to Civil Suit.`
  line `13. Obstructing Collector, &c. to be punishable by fine and in default of payment by imprisonment.`
  line `14. Collector may punish contempts.`
  line `15. Collector to act under superior revenue authorities.`
  line `16. Ground rents of East India Company to be deemed revenue within 21 Geo. 3 Cap. 70.`
  line `17. Actions for trespass or injury committed under color of Act to be tried in East India Company’s`
  line `Courts, &c. and no action to lie more than 6 months after cause arose.`
  line `18. Interprets the words “Collector” and Board of Revenue.`
  line `An Act for sec uring the Land R evenue of Madras.`
  line `Whereas it is expedient that the land revenue acc ruing due to the East India Company at Madras, within`
  line `the limits of the Town of Madras as defined in Section XII., Regulation II. of 1802., of the Madras Code,`
  line `should be ascertained and col lected in as summary a manner as in other parts of the territories under the`
  line `Government of the East India Company, It i s enacted as follows:`
  line `I. All assessable lands not the property of the East India Company, within the limits of the Town`
  line `Madras, as defined in Section XII., Regulation II. of 18 0 2, of the Madras Code, of which the rate of`
  line `assessment is not known, or which have not heretofore been assessed, shall be assessed at the rates`
  line `customarily charged upon lands of a similar description in the neighbourhood according as they may be`
  line `situated description in the neighbourhood according as they may be situated respectively within or without`
  line `the wa lls of Black Town.`
  line `II. Lakiraj tenures of land in Madras, of which uninterrupted possession has been held under alleged`
  line `grants, exempt or partially exempt from assessment for sixty years, shall be valid: no other lakiraj tenures`
  line `of land in Madras shall be deemed valid, unless the same are or shall be held under an unexpired grant from`
  line `the British Government.`
  line `III. The Collector of Madras shall determine the rate of assessment to be laid on assessable land under`
  line `Section I. of this Act, with reference to the rate assessed upon other land of a similar description in the`
  line `neighbourhood, subject to an appeal to the Board of Revenue, to be made within six months from the`
  line `notification by the Collector of the assessment fixed by him. The decision of the Board of Revenue upon`
  line `such appeal shall be final.`
obj_root_law_sections_1_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_2:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-2
  sectionNo (2)
  orderNo 2
  title `Page 2`
  content obj_root_law_sections_2_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_2_footnotes
  sourcePage 2
obj_root_law_sections_2_content:
  string
  line 2
  line `IV. The Collector may order any asse ssable land, or land already assessed, or charged with a rent`
  line `payable to the East India Company, to be measured, for the purpose of determining the amount of`
  line `assessment to be imposed, or, in the case of land already assessed or charged with a rent, for the purpose of`
  line `ascertaining whether the actual dimensions, and the dimensions upon which the amount of assessment or`
  line `rent, was calculated, correspond.`
  line `V. Whenever, upon the measurement of any land under the preceding Section, it shall be found that the`
  line `dimensions upon which the amount of assessment or rent was calculated exceed the actual dimensions, a`
  line `proportionate abatement shall be made for the excess, on the demand of the party entitle to claim it.`
  line `VI. On the other hand, when the actual dimensions exceed the dimensions upon which the amount of`
  line `assessment or rent was calculated, the excess shall be charged at the same rate as the rest of the land, the`
  line `possession being left undisturbed. Provided that, when it shall appear that the excess has been earned by`
  line `the surreptitious usurpation of ground belonging to another tenure, the act of the Collector in assessing it`
  line `sh all not prejudice the holder of such ot her tenure in any effort he m ay make to recover the ground usurped`
  line `from it. An appeal shall lie to the Board of Revenue against any extra assessment or additional rent charged`
  line `by the Collector for excess by measurement under this Section, if preferred with in six months from the date`
  line `of the Collector's order. Upon each appeal the decision of the Board of Revenue shall be final.`
  line `VII. If any owner of assessed land or any person holding land subject to a rent payable to the East India`
  line `Company, shall upon the written demand of the Collector, refuse or neglect to pay any sum at which the`
  line `land is assessed, or with which it is charged as re nt, the Collector may levy the same by distress and sale of`
  line `the goods and chattels, wherever found, of such owners or lessee; or, after written demand upon the tenant`
  line `or occupier, and of his refusal or neglect to pay the sum lawfully demanded, by distress and sale of any`
  line `goods and chattels found Upon the land, in the manner appointed for regulating distresses for small rents`
  line `in Calcutta by Act VII. of 1847, extended to Madras by Section 89, Act IX. of 1850, and for the purpose of`
  line `any such distress and sale, the Collector shall have all the powers of a Judge of the Court of Small Causes`
  line `under Section 89, Act IX. of 1850 aforesaid; and the Collector shall have power to appoint any of his`
  line `Officers to perform the duties of Bailiffs and Appraisers, and of the Chi ef Clerk of the said Court, as`
  line `provided by the said Act VII. of 1847, and all the provisions of the said Act relating to the Commissioners`
  line `for the recovery of small debts and their Court shall be deemed to apply to the said Collector and his Office`
  line `in the execution of this Act.`
  line `VIII. In the case of payment by any tenant of occupier not holding immediately under the East India`
  line `Company, or the seizure and sale of his property, he may deduct the amount of the payment or levy from`
  line `the next payment of rent to hi s landlord.`
  line `IX. The claim of the East India Company for land revenue or rent has priority over all other claims`
  line `upon the land, or to which property distrained upon the land may be liable.`
  line `X. If the Collector's claim for arrears of rent is disputed, the pro cess of distraint and sale shall not be`
  line `stayed unless the amount claimed be lodged with the Collector.`
  line `XI. Arrears of rent or revenue due to the East India Company and recoverable within six years next`
  line `after the same are due, or next after an acknowledgmen t of the same in writing has been given by the person`
  line `by whom the same is payable, or his Agent, and not afterwards.`
  line `XII. When a claim to hold land lakiraj, or free of assessment, shall be set up under this Act, the`
  line `Collector shall inquire into the claim; taking such evidence as the claimant may offer, or the public records`
  line `supply; and shall report his proceedings in the case for the consideration of the Board of Revenue. If the`
  line `Board of Revenue are satisfied of the validity of the claim, they shall make an order accordingly, and such`
  line `order shall be final. If they are not satisfied of the validity of the claim, they shall direct the Collector to`
  line `assess the land, leaving the claimant to contest the Collector's demand in the Civil Courts, as herein`
  line provided.
  line `X III. Any person obstructing or molesting the Collector, or any of his subordinate officers in the`
  line `execution of their duty, shall, on conviction before a Magistrate of the Town of Madras, be liable to a fine`
  line `not exceeding five hundred rupees, and, in defaul t of payment, to imprisonment in the common gaol for a`
  line `term not exceeding six months, or until the fine is sooner paid.`
obj_root_law_sections_2_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_3:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-3
  sectionNo (3)
  orderNo 3
  title `Page 3`
  content obj_root_law_sections_3_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_3_footnotes
  sourcePage 3
obj_root_law_sections_3_content:
  string
  line 3
  line `XIV. The Collector may punish any contempt committed in his presence in open cutcherry or office,`
  line `by fine not exceeding two hundred rupe es, and, in default of payment, by imprisonment in the common`
  line `gaol for a term not exceeding one month. From every such order of fine or imprisonment an appeal shall`
  line `lie to the Board of Revenue, whose decision shall be final.`
  line `XV. The Collector shall act in the execution of this Act, under the usual control of the superior revenue`
  line authorities.
  line `XVI. The ground rents payable to the East India Company from lands in Madras are revenue within`
  line `the meaning of the Act of Parliament, 21 Geo. III. Cap. 70; and the Supr eme Court of Judicature established`
  line `by Royal Charter at Madras has not any civil jurisdiction concerning the said ground rents, or concerning`
  line `any thing ordered or done in the assessment or collection thereof.`
  line `XVII. All actions concerning any trespass or in jury committed by any revenue officer, acting under`
  line `colour of this Act, or concerning any claim in respect of any goods taken by, or any monies paid to, any`
  line `revenue officer under this Act, or concerning any claim of rent or revenue on the part of the East India`
  line `Company under this Act, shall be tried and determined in the Civil Courts established by the East India`
  line `Company, in the Zillah of Chingleput, notwithstanding that the cause of action in respect of which such`
  line `action is brought, arose, or the defendant therein reside, within the limits of the Town of Madras, and every`
  line `such action shall be brought within six months after the cause of action arose, and not afterwards.`
  line `XVIII. The words “Collector” and “Board of Revenue” used in this Act, shall be taken to mean any`
  line `person or persons lawfully appointed to exercise the powers vested in the Collector and Board of Revenue`
  line `respectively under this Act.`
  line `_______ __`
obj_root_law_sections_3_footnotes:
  string
  line
